node.text:
Factual Tuesday

A newly released study, nailed the fact that our metabolism doesn't come to a halt, or even slow down, in fact, not until we reach the 60's, it slowly will start to drop.

Which leads me to this not so uplifting fact, which you probably already knew: Are you gaining unwanted weight, then you are eating too much, and/or are too inactive.

Our metabolism is rarely the cause of the weight gain, that most of us experience in our life, and if it was, you would feel it, not only see the weight increase on the scale. Being hypothyroid/Hashimotos (slow metabolism) has a long list of serious side effects alongside the weight gain.

So yeah, the solution which isnt new, is to move more, up your activity levels, drop the take out, skip the highly processed foods, say no thank's to junk food, and implement some healthier alternatives instead. Not only to help you balance your weight, but also to pay of health wise in a hopefully long and joyful life.

Happy Tuesday.

https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34385400/

#healthiswealth #weightlossinspiration #lifestylechange #lifehack

node.text:
Yay to all them natural flaws we carry with us

Let's rewind and rephrase flaws to something like: Natural, signs of life and growth

Because the cellulite on my arms, booty, thighs and hamstrings, the lose skin on my tummy, my stretchmarks, arent to be considered as flaws, because they are not.

Very unfortunately its still portrayed as such, especially in the "beauty" industry where everything has to be elite, polished and fake, to a degree which would make it unrealistic in real life. The word perfect is often used for the images and models you see on high fashion blogs and magazines, but shouldnt perfect be replaced with unrealistic and highly edited instead, considering that 95% of women have either cellulite or stretchmarks?

Well, wishful thinking I know, but could we all please shout it out loud, that there's nothing wrong with having cellulite, folds, scars, stretchmarks and freckles, periodt.

Happy Monday

#cellulite #stretchmarks #bodytransformation #strongwomen

node.text:
Insecurities in men

Is a real thing, which often leads them to rage out on social media against women, me included.

- You look like a man
- You got thick knees and ankles
- You are fat, not fit
- Look at that masculine jaw
- You got hairy arms and legs
- Muscles are for men only
- All those muscles and only one pull up, weak
- I bet you have a weenie

Just to mention a few! I simply cant help but feel sorry for these men, they obviously feel jalous, intimidated and lack confidence. No person within reasonable doubt, point their finger at other people's look's without feeling sh1t about themselves to begin with, that's an undeniable fact, and even proven in a recent released survey.

Man up guys, it testifies clearly that youre weak, if pointing fingers at women makes you feel more Manly, that's pathetic.

Note: This isnt a rant against all men, there's way more true gentlemen out there than dickweeds, fact.

Happy Weekend

#confidence #weak #beyourself #strongwomen

node.text:
Factual Tuesday

The Danish medic group Novo Nordic, have made a breakthrough in regards to weight loss medication (Wegovy). It works simply by suppressing hunger, and as of now, it has shown be really effective at keeping the weight off too.

But - People still keep their unhealthy lifestyle that lead them into obesity to start with, that's not good. In most obesity related issues, its not the weight itself that causes issues, but the amount of highly processed calorie dense foods, and lack of exercise, that leads to cardiac issues, blood clots, arterary disease, high cholesterol, diabetes, screwed hormones and weight gain, obviously.

Medication is great and can help us get far, but choosing an approach geared towards more mindful living, a higher level of activity, eating more protein and eating more whole foods, will benefit us a millions times more than tanking up on "magic" injections and pills.

Health is wealth guys, take care of it, it's the only one we have and we should cheerish it.

#healthiswealth #feels #youvsyou #healthyhabits
